CONSULTATION COMPLETE! Wait, this wasn’t a consultation at all! This was more like a visit with a good friend that you haven’t seen in a while! Todays visit brings us back to sunny Melbourne Florida, about an hour east of Orlando. For anyone who would remember, we were here about a year ago doing our first consult with Billy Ellis, the owner of Tintology. For those that didn’t know, Tintology is an XPEL certified install center based in Melbourne, and Billy is an incredibly talented film installer whose skills are highly regarded nationally. Billy has been tapped many times to lead trainings at large events around the nation, he’s certainly a man of talent!

When we originally came down here to Melbourne, Billy and his wife Kristina took amazing care of us and were incredibly hospitable. This time around was no different, and there was lots of laughs and discussion over the day. Billy even introduced us to a customer that originally came in from one of our social media ads in the beginning of the year and since that time has brought or referred more than a DOZEN PPF jobs! How is that for acquisition value! Sometimes you don’t just get one job from an ad: you get 12! 

Billy pulled me. aside just before we took this photo and put $100 in my hand. “I see you always giving out $100 to people, I wanted to give $100 to you.” And he slips a benjamin in my hand. “Take Jessica out somewhere nice for dinner” he told me. Haha. She’s not even fancy! 

More than anything else, we are thankful for the opportunity to work with Billy and other business owners like him around the globe who are chasing their dreams and making their own way. It’s a crazy life, but it’s never boring! 

Thank you for having us back Billy! 🚀 @tintologyprotectivefilms @tintologybilly @tintology_xtina @jessicadsapp

Trying to recap an entire year can be overwhelming, both for a person to type and for you to read. Without leaving a ton of stuff out, how can you really look back on all the memories, adventures, growth and experience of an entire year? I’ll just share some numbers that we figured out over the past week.

2022 Fun Stats 😵‍💫

•312 Workouts
•56 Flights
•20 States Visited 
•16 Marketing Consultations 
•9 Concerts
•7 Public Speaking Engagements
•4 Vehicles Purchased
•3 Stadium Events Hosted

This year I also achieved a 700+ credit score, paid off a major credit line, got my first AMEX and hit status with American Airlines. I visited Hawaii for the first time, did an EPIC Route 66 road trip, explored British Columbia, New York 4 times, California 4 times, and Florida 5 times!! And that’s just a brief summary!!!

All of this, literally every aspect of what I do, is backed up by my incredible partner Jessica. You really can’t think of me without thinking of her too, because we’re basically inseparable and she’s a part of every project, trip and event I have. She’s an absolutely one of a kind person, and it should go without me saying it how thankful I am for her every day!

The list of people I should thank for everything that happened in 2022 is too long to list. Forgive me. Among the numerous that deserve a mention are my Mom & Dad, My Event Staff & Volunteers, Our Clients, Dylan and Pedro, Lisa my Banker, and all of my friends, followers and fans. I love you all so much.

2023 has no reason to be any less exciting than 2022 was, and from what I can see so far it’s going to be our most ridiculous year yet. Will you come along with me for the ride? 

The best is yet to come. Happy New Year!

CONSULTATION COMPLETE! I forgot to even tell you guys, we’re here in Pennsylvania! Jessica and I took off Wednesday morning for Washington DC and then drove a rental car two hours to Chambersburg PA for a full day consultation. To get here we had to drive up from Virginia and through Maryland. The layout up here is so different from Texas.

Our client for this visit is a shop called Sun Protectors. This is an XPEL film shop with a specific proficiency in window film. The owner Brian has been doing it since the early 90’s! This business is nearly 30 years old now. That’s a long time slinging film! 

Up until this point Sun Protectors has been running their marketing themselves but after several conversations last year they decided to fly us out to build their new campaigns and do some content coaching. Darren the marketing manager had taken a ton of notes at XDC22 in my class and I could literally see the difference with his content. Well done! 

Jessica did her normal wizardry, and once again got into the CRM (Tint Wiz) and was able to properly integrate all the systems together. When you can have Google Analytics, Tag Manager, Ads, YouTube, Facebook, the CRM and your websites server all communicating: cool stuff can happen!

I really connected with Brian and Darren on this visit. Both of them share a lot of my fundamental beliefs and core values. One of the coolest moments of the visit was Brian telling me how he referred a particular PPF job to another XPEL dealer 30 minutes up the road. The job was worth $8k, but Brian knew the shop up the road was a better fit for that particular clients needs.

That’s not doing the profitable thing. 
That’s doing the right thing.

Brian mentioned several friends and mentors he has in the industry. Alex and Dean especially, but many more of you. My favorite part? Nothing but positive things to say. No negativity, just positive vibes! 👏

We’re thankful for the opportunity to help your business Brian! And James we missed you buddy!

I just got the word that our friend Nick Mahler has passed away. I am absolutely heartbroken and shocked. Nick was such a character, he was so supportive and kind. Hilarious. Original. He attended everything I did, from my 30th birthday party to my stadium events to my marketing classes. He attended again and again. 

Nick had a super rare disease called Fibrodysplasia Ossificans Progressiv, or FOP. It sounds like something out of Game of Thrones or Harry Potter, but simply explained progressively through life, muscles and tendons are gradually transformed into bone. Anytime Nick would get an injury or bump, the body would heal and turn into bone. Slowly, Nick was becoming trapped inside of his own body with less and less mobility as the years went on.

All that pain and frustration is over for him now. Thank goodness.

Nick didn’t let his disability define him. Even in his specialized chair, he was a larger than life character, out spoken and quick witted, he constantly shocked me with jokes and sharp remarks that had my class attendees in stitches. He was seriously terrific.

He will be greatly missed.

I am sharing terrible news. This morning at 5:45am I woke up to a phone call from my Dad. The home of my 91 year grandmother Alma was up in flames in Pleasant Grove. My mom and dad were headed to the house to get more information. 

When they arrived Dallas FD was still on the scene fighting the fire. The entire roof was already gone, at least half of the structure was lost. Not much details there. My understanding is that the home and everything in it is a total loss. It was full of family heirlooms, photos and records than can never be replaced.

Alma got out of the house, but we don’t have any details. We do know that she was transported to Parkland Hospital via ambulance, with a pulse. For whatever reasons the FD is being scant on specifics, so we don’t know if she was injured, burned, or what condition she is in at all. All we know is that she was alive when they got her into the ambulance.

The last time I spoke to Grandma was when I got back from Mexico. She had called, like she always does, on my Birthday to sing me Happy Birthday. I still have the voicemail saved. We spoke for a while and she was in good spirits. For someone in her 90’s she’s still pretty sharp, well spoken and has a great sense of humor. I love her so much.

She is my last remaining grandparent.

My only hope today is that will be ok. For now, that is all I can do. 🙏

Why does it take tragedy to bring clarity? In the hours after something unthinkable, truths become obvious. I’m struggling with grief in a very deep and profound way today. When time is up, you can immediately realize how well you used the time you had.

I could have done better. I should have done better.

Grandma would never say something negative to me. She was always simply loving, patient and kind. I wish I had spent more time with her. I should have.

You assume they will always just be there tomorrow. They always have been.

And then they’re not.

At this point all you can do is evaluate what you did with the time you had. And all I can think about is “Not Enough”. Not enough.

Thinking this isn’t productive, and it’s not going to change anything. But I keep thinking it anyways.

I don’t want to think this again. I can’t change the past but I can decide what I do from here.

I don’t want the people that I love to just hear it. I want them to know it. Grandma made me feel that way. 

But I’m not sure if I returned the favor.

A lot of you reading won’t care or understand, but I’m just going to share anyways because I’m a nerd. I’m super thrilled for my new wheels, these gorgeous vintage SSR Forged Auswuch’s in 15”x8”. They are currently in Japan, and being loaded onto a pallet to be shipped here to Texas. They are for the Delica.

I love these wheels because they are period appropriate, manufactured in the early 90’s when the Star Wagon was in production, so these are the exact kind of wheels you would have seen on a Delica in the 90’s. Even better, this specific set has a -1 offset, which is perfect for fitment on this model.

I was optimistic and excited about Reels Play Bonus, but it was never money I was used to making anyways. If the only reason you produce content at all is to benefit yourself, you’re already taking an approach that is destined to fail.

I went to visit Grandma today. She is buried at Grove Hill Memorial Park in Dallas. Turns out she paid for this exact spot, and the entire occasion more than a decade ago. This whole thing has been absolutely surreal for me over the past 16 days. How can you ever be ready? 

Grandma lived an awesome life of 91 years. While I can’t help but be thankful that I got this much time with her, I’m still struggling with the thought that she was robbed in the 11th hour of what could have very well been several more years of memories. I go back and forth a lot mentally between happiness and sadness. It’s hard.

At the end of it all people remember is how you made them feel. Nobody is talking about the money she made or lost, the cars she bought or sold, the trips she went on or didn’t. Really none of that matters at all. But how she treated us? How she made me feel? 

That’s the the legacy of a person!

That’s also how, really, a person can never truly die if you remember them. How could I ever forget? A huge part of who I am, how I think, and how I act is because of this woman. She’s a part of me. She always will be.

I hate seeing a pile of dirt, somehow it seems disrespectful to a person so important to so many, someone who had such an epic life full of love and adventures. If I had it my way, she would have an entire monument erected to pay testament to the magnitude of her importance!

But that’s not what she wanted, and she wouldn’t care about that anyways. She didn’t have some grand vision to be adored by strangers, she just wanted to live life her own way and be a part of the family she created. And she did. She did it! A life well lived.👏

I’ll never stop missing you Grandma! Enjoy the rest you earned, and I’ll see you when I get there. ❤️

The famous “Lower Broadway” in downtown Nashville, home of iconic Honky Tonks, neon lit bars and live music galore! This place grew up in the shadow of the Ryman Auditorium, the original location of the Grand Ole Opry. The Opry relocated in the 70’s by today lower Broadway is a major tourist destination of its own.

Having traveled so much I can say that this place gives me vibes of Fremont Street in Vegas, 6th Street in Austin, and Burbon Street in New Orleans. It has characteristics of each of them, but is uniquely Nashville and a massive country vibe on top.

On Broadway it seems that every bride to be within 600 miles has made her way here with friends in tow to live it up one more time before tying the knot. Young women wearing white sachets and even crowns are so plentiful here that they nearly trip over one another! Many of them wear crispy new knee high white leather cowboy boots. It’s fascinating.

Jessica and I don’t drink, and we also don’t stay out late, so people like us aren’t exactly the target market for a place like this. Still, both of us can appreciate the hype and history of a place, the people watching is interesting and the lights, sounds and overall atmosphere is really exciting to be immersed in. For me, I can get a real kick out of just waking around and checking out the clubs from the outside. I counted at least 20 live bands, and this was a weeknight.

A lot of people are sleeping on Nashville. 

Being here every 3 months it’s very apparent and obvious that there is an exploding economy here, massive tourism and ever expanding and improving infrastructure. The airport, for example, is one of the nicest ones in the nation, and I’ve seen most of them.

I nearly bought Jessica a pair of unbelievable Turquoise cowboy boots, but didn’t pull the trigger. She told me that she couldn’t imagine when she would wear them.

She said she likes this one. 💁‍♂️

A new Guinness World Record was set in North Richland Hills on 7/3/23 by Sky Elements Drones. The previous record for "Largest aerial sentence formed by multirotors/ drones" was 673. Now it is 796. Explained more easily, this is a GWR for the amount of drones used to make words in the sky. Nobody in history has ever used more for this purpose.

Like my second and third Guinness World Records, I served as a consultant on this project. One of the co-founders of Sky Elements Drones took my Facebook class a few years ago, and reached out to Jessica and I to help grow their company as well as differentiate them from the competition. That was a while back, and the rest as they sav is history...
The company has had meteoric growth during our time on the team, and is easily the dominant provider of commercial quality drone shows in the United States. Clients include Sony, Marvel, Netflix, Microsoft, Universal, Coca-Cola and a host of MLB, NHL and MLS teams. It's been unbelievable.

Each time I've got to celebrate with people I love and respect as they had their own EPIC moment just like I did in 2016.
Anyone who pulls one of these off will tell you it takes an army. There are so many people who all do incredible work to make these things possible, and no less than 100 individuals (or more) went into this achievement by Sky Elements Drones. Jessica personally handled the livestream for the company on IG from the roof of the Delica.

Walt Disney said "If you can dream it, you can do it". The best part of what I do for a living is that I get to help our clients achieve their dreams. Watching an idea become reality as the clients hold a world record over their heads with fireworks blasting a finale just behind them is a memory I will never, ever forget. Officially Amazing!

I own approximately 100 pairs of shoes. Here are some insights I have learned so far that you may find interesting.

* Comfort is King. Despite having a pretty big selection to choose from I keep coming back to shoes that are the most comfortable. These tend to be some of the most boring shoes of all. HOKA Bondi 8, Brooks Trace 2, Adidas 4DFWD are in weekly use. 

* Shoes with function. Because I am actively weight training I wear training shoes. My NOBULL trainers are worn weekly thanks to their dense hard rubber bottoms. I also have specific shoes tor hiking, running, leg day, the beach, a rodeo, riding a motorcycle or even go kart racing.

* I prefer obnoxious colors. Because life is short and it makes people look I naturally gravitate to shoes with neon colors, lights, glow in the dark functions or even crystals.

* Stick with what you like. Once you have a style you like, it makes sense to get the same shoe in different colors. My most popular styles in my collection are Yeezy 350’s, Yeezy 700’s and Jordan 5 Retro’s.

* What shoes do I love the most? Of all the shoes I own, the most fun have easily been the Dolce & Gabbana Crystal Sorrento’s and the Balmain Unicorns. In both cases the shoes are are rare, loud and obnoxious that people can’t help but ask questions and comment on them. That’s the entire point and I consider such interactions a “ROI” on the purchase. 

* Keep them clean. You can maintain a pair of shoes for a long time if you clean them regularly. My nicer sets get a wipe down after each use to keep them in peak shape.

* If it’s fun, it’s fine. At the end of the day some people get it and some people don’t, and neither is really right or wrong. If it’s fun and you like it, go for it! 

If you have any shoe questions I’m always happy to help!

Here’s to Shelley Sax-Eldridge of Stern Pinball. Most of my audience reading this won’t know about her, and that’s ok. However there is almost a 100% chance you have enjoyed or seen something she’s helped make possible. Shelley was a critical component in the business of building more than 100 pinball machine titles over nearly 40 years! Inside the company they referred to her at the J.O.A.T, or “Jill of All Trades”. She was a Swiss Army knife of a team member, dependable and capable for virtually everything.

Shelley was really around for the earliest days of Data East Pinball, which later would become Stern Pinball. Gary Stern has always spoke extremely highly of her, insisting that there would never have even been a Stern Pinball without Shelley. I am sure he’s right.

Shelley was quietly fighting a brave battle against cancer for many years. She had recently retired, but I don’t think anyone could ever be mentally prepared someone as strong and as consistent and dependable as Shelley to not be around. In regards to Stern, only Gary himself could say he was around longer. Considering how often he travels internationally, it’s likely true that nobody in history spent more days inside a pinball machine manufacturing facility than her.

She was the first person who opened the door for me the day I showed up to interview for my original position as Social Media Director for the company in 2015. Smiles and kindness every time. She was such a badass. She will be greatly missed.

MY REAL NUMBERS AUGUST = $530.25 total in Meta Monetization payout. Being absolutely transparent and real with you guys, I just finished my first ever month in the “Performance Bonus” program here on META. Performance bonus pays on everything EXCEPT for stories and reels. 

Facebook Performance Bonus was $311.56
Facebook Ads on Reels Bonus was $218.69
Instagram Based Bonus was N/A

What I love about performance bonus is that it does not place a single ad on your feed, or even change how you see my content. Even better, I have not changed or modified how often I share content. This is just business as usual for me.

If I had been enrolled in the performance bonus when my viral Barbie post hit, I would have made several thousand dollars easily. Oh well, maybe next time! 

$530 is not enough to quit a job, but it’s a lot more than I had been paid to share my own content since 2007, which generally has been zero. For 16 years, I’ve been doing this for free.

And that’s the correct approach.

As soon as you are creating content with the sole and specific intention to create value for yourself, it’s going to fail. It’s only by creating content for the sake of the audience that you can succeed. ￼💯

But THIS particular charge stings…

Because THIS is the charge for food I didn’t sell. 🥴

You see, my contract stipulated a “guaranteed food and beverage minimum” and since I didn’t meet it: I am contractually obligated to pay the difference. Turns out, that difference was about $12,500. 😳

The cost business was always defined, and is always a massive risk, but a calculated one. I did not, however, expect or calculate the expense of ghost hot dogs. 😂

“My name is Jared Guynes. I believe in my dreams and believe that everyone should chase them. I also now know that sometimes, in the pursuit of a dream, you might end up unintentionally spending $10,000+ on phantom hot dogs that were never cooked.”🥴

Here is how this game is going to work. Every Wednesday I am going to continue to post a photo of me and Jessica eating bagels at The Bagel Lady in Rockwall Texas. You are going to casually come across this post, and likely not only engage, comment or leave any visible evidence you ever saw it.

You are also not going to drive to Rockwall, plan a trip to Rockwall, or for those of you who happen to be in or near Rockwall, you won’t go to The Bagel Lady. All of that takes time, money, effort. Who has time for that?

So I keep posting every Wednesday, and one day or another, I wear you down. You give up. Either you stop seeing my posts whatsoever, or, eventually, you cave and seemingly spontaneously decide to in fact go and eat the bagel: like the picture you saw online.

What you’re seeing here is called “guerilla marketing” or more obvious in the modern age “influencer marketing”. This is where intentional communication by someone you trust persuades you to make a financial transaction.

The interesting bit though, is that I’m NOT being paid, compensated, traded or even asked to do this. I’m doing it because I feel like it. I want to do it.👏

This type of authentic, genuine embracement of a brand or services has been a thing forever. The difference is, these days, culture has manipulated us all into believing that we should only help when it benefits us, share when it pays us, speak up when it is in our own financial best interest…

It’s hard to tell what people really like: and what they are paid to like. 🤔

I really, really like the bagels at The Bagel Lady. I believe in them. I believe in Revi and her dream. I want them to succeed.

So I’m going to keep sharing a photo every Wednesday.

And one day or another, money is going to leave your pocket and go into hers.

ARE YOU DONE? Now that Black Friday and Cyber Monday are over, the text messages and the emails have calmed down. You spent more money on Amazon in the past 5 days than you’d like to admit. Did you remember that a locally owned small business in your community didn’t really have the ability or the budget to do a Black Friday or Cyber Monday sale? They need you to remember.

In advertising we talk about metrics like “frequency” which has to do with the amount of times you are exposed to a brand/service/product. The general consensus is that if you can increase the frequency of exposure: you increase the likelihood of a transaction.

The problem of course is that small brands can’t often afford enough frequency to catch your attention. Even when they can, you can’t always act on it, and then later you forget. This is a constant problem for small businesses on a tight budget. 

Ultimately I believe a cultural “philosophy shift” is the only real solution. What I mean is that we need people to naturally and instinctively prioritize doing business with local companies whenever possible. This may mean waiting a little longer, paying a little more, or driving a little further. We have invested to much into “convenience” that we have sold our soul to have it…

The soul of America is small business. It’s what makes your town unique. It’s the cast of characters that makes you proud to from where you are from. We don’t need to lose that. 

You don’t need a promo code or a doorbuster to support small business. You just need to remember.

Less than two weeks ago I was made aware of Lucas, the little boy from Quinlan Texas whose family were told on December 12th he likely has just months left. Lucas has been diagnosed with (diffuse intrinsic pontine glioma) or DIPG, a brain cancer that can only be delayed: not stopped. Every second of every day is critical for Lucas and his family.

Not that Lucas knows or understands any of this, nor should he. I’m a full grown adult and I don’t understand it either. Situations like this defy understanding. 

Here is what I did know. For a single night, I would have the keys to one of the world’s finest arenas and I would be hosting the 14th iteration of my signature family blaster event. As fate would have it, Lucas is a massive Nerf fan, and his condition has not just worsened to a point where he can not play and run like any other child. So we went to work.

There are too many details to share, but the culmination of the effort led to Lucas himself joining me atop the stage in front of thousands of cheering kids, and raising his hand high above his head. My heart was so full, as my entire events attendance joined me in celebrating and cheering for Lucas!

For a moment: Lucas was the King of the stadium. The Ultimate VIP. ✨

I’ve been doing these events for 8 years, and I’ve been blessed to meet so many amazing kids and incredible parents. Across the nation I’ve had the honor of being a small part of tens of thousands of families core memories. But this moment stands at the top of that pile as one of the most impactful memories of them all.

My memory of Lucas will always be him smiling, hand raised above his head. #LucasStrong 

📸 - Brandon Hollien / Brandon Hollien Photography

If I was lazy and average I could just say “Happy Wednesday!” Or “It’s Bagel Wednesday!” That’s boring. That’s easy, that’s expected. It’s 2024 and you can’t just post lazy content on social media and reasonably expect it to reach anyone. Sorry. Facts.

The best content creates an “emotional response” and that’s a bit of an art. For me, it’s telling authentic stories. Sharing my perspective with words that people read silently on their phones. Statistically speaking most people who follow me online have never heard me speak live in person. It’s weird!

My weekly effort to take and share photos of bagels on Wednesday is called “Guerrilla Marketing” and it’s a topic I explain in my classes. The idea is that I can expose you to a brand, product or experience in a way that gives that brand, product or experience better odds of getting money from you. Many of you do this all time, unwittingly, totally on accident. Reviews, testimonials, etc. Same thing. 

Anyways, Revi (who owns the Bagel Lady) does not pay me a dollar, we do not have an arrangement. She’s not a client. She is a friend, but I’m a true and genuine customer. I pay full price and tip 20% every single week. I have the receipts. 

So why the guerilla marketing effort then?

Because I want to help keep her business alive. Because I know it matters. Because I don’t want to see them fail. Because my bagel every Wednesday is a foundational part of my schedule and life at home. 

So yeah I could have just posted “Happy Wednesday” but that would be way too easy to ignore and scroll past. In fact the algorithm would likely choose to never even show you that post to begin with…

But it showed you this one. Didn’t it? Here you are reading. That’s the point! That’s the intention!

Now are you gonna go buy a bagel? Probably not. You’re busy. You don’t live in Texas. You’ve been meaning to get around to it. I get it. But..

If this post reminds even a single person to go try them, or go and try them again: it was worth it. And I’d be willing to bet that will happen. So I will continue.

Happy Wednesday. 😉 #EatLocal

If you know someone who loves cars: this is one of the best gift ideas ever! Petrol Vibes lets you submit photos of your exact car with its specific accessories and mods, and they made a laser cut steel art of it for you to hang on the wall! Made to order! Super happy with this gift of my L300 Delica! They even got the little ladder and the awning on the passenger side! Epic!!! #PetrolVibes #Delica #L300 #WallArt #LaserCut #Cars #CarGuy #Gift #VanLife @petrolvibes_

Special shoutout to Jessica, who secretly took photos of my Delica and sent them to Petrol Vibes, who then made a vector outline of it. From there they used a laser cutter to make a 4’ scale replica of the van from steel, and then they powder coated it black. It’s not like the have a database of every car, this was the first time they have ever been asked to do a Delica, and they even added the awning and ladder, which are specific accessories on my van. 

She suprised me with it for Christmas, but I’ve waited to share a post about it until I could take a photo of it and the van at the same time. 😊

I made a reel about it that’s cooler to see than this photo, but not everyone sees everything I post anyways. Mostly I’m surprised that Jessica would think of something so specific and thoughtful for me. @petrolvibes_

I have decided to put my entire collection of blaster toys (Nerf / X-Shot / Adventure Force) for sale. I will donate every penny generated from this sale to the family of Lucas. For the few that may see this post and somehow not know who Lucas is, he is the little boy from Quinlan Texas that is fighting advanced DIPG brain cancer. He’s only 7. 

While I cannot begin to imagine or understand the pain and stress Lucas’ family is coping with, I know that their expenses must be overwhelming. 

I am still working on the date, but I plan to host the sale at Shenaniganz in Rockwall. I’ll price everything fairly, but there will be the opportunity for you to pay/donate more, if you want. I also would welcome some brave local company to step up and agree to match my donation so we can double it. Stay tuned for more.

If you have used blaster toys you would like to bring to donate so they can be added to our effort, that’s fine. My collection is very large, likely 300-500 toys. Too many to count easily. 

And finally, as for Mr. Beast, we have hundreds of people working on this, but as of the time of this post we have not yet heard any official response or acknowledgement. So that effort continues. Lucas is still here, there is still time for that miracle. Keep sharing that post. 

Thanks for your support. #LucasStrong #LucasDIPG

Can I just brag on Jessica Sapp for a minute? Among her long list of admirable attributes I could write, here is one of my favorites: how she treats animals. She loves all animals, but none more than her own baby, Chance. She takes the absolute utmost care of him, going to extraordinary lengths to prepare him for the cold weather, as you can see here. Leg warmers. Hoodie. Insulated jacket. He wears the colors of the Jessica Sapp style guide. 

Note she puts on his jacket first before she puts on her own.

A lot of owners would let the dog out on their own, and I get that, but here we have rattlesnakes, rabbits, possums and all kinds of animals around. To make sure Chance doesn’t get hurt, Jessica personally accompanies him out to potty. Every time.

She cuts his nails every week.
She brushes his teeth every week.
She feeds him human grade food every day.

This dog even gets special daily vitamins. I don’t even take vitamins! 😂

Our professional career has to do with a lot of fine details. The companies who invest into us have to trust that we can see things they don’t see, do things they can’t do, and care just as much about their brands as they do. To see how someone will be in a professional capacity, just look how they are in a personal capacity. 

Jessica takes special care and attention of every detail of her life. “Above and beyond” is totally normal for her. I don’t ever take it for granted either, I’m thankful every single day.😁

So is Chance. 😅

A lot of hate for EV’s going around this winter. Seems some people are getting a reality check about range issues. My bolt for example, is now only able to run 200 miles on a full charge, VS 250-270 in the summer. It’s true: drastic cold temperatures reduce EV range. 👎

Thankfully for me, I rarely if ever need to drive more than 200 miles in a single day. Reports say that most Americans are in the same boat. 💁‍♂️

Meanwhile, my brand new Duramax 2500HD failed to start the other day when it was 11°. I forgot to plug in the engine heater, and I neglected to add diesel fuel additive to the tank. The result was my truck literally refusing to turn over and throwing a CEL. What if this was my only vehicle? Luckily for me, my trusty little EV fired right up. The range may be reduced but at least it worked. 🙌

Rather than proclaim that any one car is right or wrong, I contend that cars are like tools: some tools are right or wrong for certain jobs. Different people will present specific scenarios or data that paint something better than the other. It’s subjective.

My little battery powered Chevy gets almost 160mpg equivalent. For 90% of my actual weekly transportation needs: that’s totally fine.
